Subject: Dang Hu Games: Game 10 ('Final')
Message-ID: <1992Aug27.015118.9648@news.acns.nwu.edu>
Date: 27 Aug 92 01:51:18 GMT
Article-I.D.: news.1992Aug27.015118.9648
Sender: usenet@news.acns.nwu.edu (Usenet on news.acns)
Organization: Northwestern University, Evanston Illinois.
Lines: 799

Hi, everyone!

Here we go -- the final game of the Dang Hu Games.  This game actually
appeared in this same newsgroup before, posted by jansteen.  On first look
they looked like two different games, but a closer look told me that they
were the same game shown from two different angles.

Thus an idea stroke me; I would like to take this opportunity to post the
following question: Assume a Go game is highly asymmetric (which is the
case in almost all played Go games), how many outlooks a single game can
have?  That is, you can turn the Go board 90 degrees or 270 degrees, for
example, but you know that is the same game you're looking at.

Of course, the board has to be always upright standing on the screen of
your terminal; you can not turn the board by, say, 1 degree or 2 -- that
will be very uninteresting.

Simple, isn't it?  Well, that's what I have in mind.  After playing so
many hard games, I would like everyone to do some simple exercises like
this.  But, please, answer it!

So I can laugh at you . :)))))

Okay so I hope everyone to have some fun, and I certainly have not
forgotten my promise to dedicate every game to a person who has helped me
to learn and play Go.  This game, Game 10 of Dang Hu Games, is dedicated to
*eightk*, who is not an 8 kyu. :)

He taught me Go.

jzy 2k ^_^

